The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro

On amp; Off

City scores a seven

Stage On amp; Off

 Students rehearse for the Sangeet Natak Akademi finale on Saturday at Sisir Mancha. Picture by Aranya Sen

 Calcutta theatre stole the thunder from a bouquet of big names at the first Mahindra Excellence in Theatre Awards (META), held in Delhi from February 6 to 10, bagging seven of the 20 awards. Ranan?s Crossings, directed by Vikram Iyengar, brought home four awards, while Rangakarmee?s Sarhad Paar Manto, steered by Usha Ganguli, bagged three.

 Eight plays in either Hindi or English were shortlisted for the theatre festival-cum-awards ceremony from Calcutta, Delhi, Mumbai and Bangalore. The prizes were given away in two categories of emerging and established theatre.

 In emerging theatre, Crossings bagged four awards ? Nageen Tanvir for best innovative sound design, Vikram Iyengar for best direction and best costume design, and Archana Ramaswamy for best supporting actress.

 The jury for the awards comprised Shabana Azmi, M.S. Sathyu, Ila Arun, Zafar Hai, Shyamanand Jalan and M.K. Raina.

 In established theatre, Sarhad Paar Manto bagged the awards for best innovative sound design, best set design (by Khaled Choudhury) and best overall production. In this category, Mumbai-based Lillete Dubey fetched the best director award for Sammy!, Joy Sengupta and Shahid Siddiqui shared the best actor (male) award for Sammy! and Witness for the Prosecution, while the best actor (female) award went to Nalini for her role in Witness for the Prosecution. Partap Sharma won the best original script award for Sammy!.

 In emerging theatre, Satyajit Sharma won the best actor (male) award for Peele Scooterwaala Aadmi, while Seema Agrawal was chosen best actor (female) for Rabi?a. Manav Kaul won the best original script award for Peele Scooterwaala Aadmi.

 The awards were announced and given away by Amal Allana, Ritu Kumar, Nandita Das, Joy Michael and Roshan Seth. The evening featured performances by Shabana Azmi and Farooque Shaikh (Tumhari Amrita), Ila Arun (Jameela Bai Kalaali) and Dadi Pudumjee?s Ishara Puppet Theatre. 

 Girija Devi, Mrinal Sen and Goutam Ghose confer the Legends of India Lifetime Achievement for Theatre on Badal Sircar at Swabhumi on Thursday. Picture by Aranya Sen

 The second phase of the theatre-training programme conducted by Sangeet Natak Akademi is over. Now it?s the turn of the students to display samples of their newly acquired skills. The students will put up four short plays they have directed, designed and performed, on February 18 at Sisir Mancha. 

 During the 75-day workshop held with the support of Padatik at Joka, young theatre artistes from the country?s eastern zone were trained in acting, direction, set, light and costume design, theatre music, make-up, mime, yoga etc. Among those who took classes at Joka were Ratan Thiyam, Satish Anand, K.N. Panikkar, P.K.G. Nambiar, Birjit Ngangomba and Shashadhar Acharya.




